00:00:02.420 --> 00:00:03.580
MALE SPEAKER: "The Skeptics
Guide to the Mind--

00:00:03.580 --> 00:00:05.790
What Neuroscience Can and
Cannot Tell Us about

00:00:05.790 --> 00:00:09.570
Ourselves." The first two
chapters are about out of body

00:00:09.570 --> 00:00:13.760
experiences, phantom limbs,
problems assigning agency to

00:00:13.760 --> 00:00:15.610
our own actions.

00:00:15.610 --> 00:00:20.720
And Doctor Burton describes many
of the same reports that

00:00:20.720 --> 00:00:24.410
are trotted out in the scores
of popular books on

00:00:24.410 --> 00:00:24.960
computation--

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:27.150
on Neuroscience and
the brain--

00:00:27.150 --> 00:00:30.800
more often than not, with
some of the unsupported

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:33.970
interpretations that are
floating around about what

00:00:33.970 --> 00:00:36.320
this data means.

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:38.685
He points out that even
reputable Neuroscientists are

00:00:38.685 --> 00:00:41.570
as quick to fuel the public
appetite for disturbing

00:00:41.570 --> 00:00:46.440
anecdotes and attention
getting soundbites.

00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:50.590
What Robert's book helps the
reader to do is to revisit

00:00:50.590 --> 00:00:53.480
some of the many patient cases,
animal studies, MRI

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:56.710
recordings, from a different
perspective, offering

00:00:56.710 --> 00:01:00.280
alternative explanations and
dissecting the way these

00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:02.970
results are explained in
the popular press.

00:01:02.970 --> 00:01:05.990
And why so many of those
explanations are misleading,

00:01:05.990 --> 00:01:09.740
premature, and needlessly
theatrical, essentially

00:01:09.740 --> 00:01:12.940
pandering to our high opinion
of our own vaunted brains.

00:01:15.730 --> 00:01:19.520
But having studying Neuroscience
for now about 20

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:21.350
years about 10 years--
excuse me--

00:01:21.350 --> 00:01:23.690
it seems--

00:01:23.690 --> 00:01:26.800
and taught a course at Stanford,
I thought I was

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:30.000
pretty savvy about neuroscience
and the ability

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.530
to parse out the true
facts and reading

00:01:33.530 --> 00:01:34.900
some of these papers.

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:38.260
But in several instances, Robert
helped me to recognize

00:01:38.260 --> 00:01:42.130
how I had allowed language and
hyperbole surrounding the

00:01:42.130 --> 00:01:46.100
public versions of these
scientific studies to

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:49.780
insinuate itself into
my scientific view.

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:53.440
Robert's new book seeks to
exorcise some of these

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:55.960
comfortable and often
compelling, but ultimately

00:01:55.960 --> 00:02:00.100
misleading, views of
Neuroscience It's

00:02:00.100 --> 00:02:01.470
a thoughtful book.

00:02:01.470 --> 00:02:04.120
It's a really intriguing
and fun book to read.

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:06.765
And I'm looking forward to
what he has to say today.

00:02:06.765 --> 00:02:08.665
ROBERT BURTON: Thanks, Tom.

00:02:08.665 --> 00:02:12.950
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:12.950 --> 00:02:15.440
Is that too loud
or just right?

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:16.210
It's OK?

