00:02:23.650 --> 00:02:26.240
ROBERT BURTON: And if you guys
have to leave now, this slide

00:02:26.240 --> 00:02:32.840
sort of is the main takeaway,
namely, though we don't like

00:02:32.840 --> 00:02:36.370
to admit it, the tools of
Neuroscience are not fMRI

00:02:36.370 --> 00:02:38.620
scans and inter-cellular
recordings.

00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:42.680
The primary tool for studying
the mind, as opposed to the

00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:44.700
brain, is the mind itself.

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:46.520
We dream up to questions.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:48.200
We dream up the experiments.

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:50.910
We write the algorithms
for the fMRI.

00:02:50.910 --> 00:02:53.180
We interpret the results.

00:02:53.180 --> 00:02:57.230
And herein lies Problem A, which
we're not going to go

00:02:57.230 --> 00:02:59.170
into any further, which
is the polemic of the

00:02:59.170 --> 00:03:00.420
mind studying itself.

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:08.290
What I really wanted to talk
about today is to what extent

00:03:08.290 --> 00:03:12.970
our own brains shape the way
we conceptualize the mind.

00:03:12.970 --> 00:03:14.750
Let me just start by asking
a simple question.

00:03:14.750 --> 00:03:19.690
How many of you people think
that the brain is the mind?

00:03:19.690 --> 00:03:19.970
OK.

00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:24.480
How many people think the brain
emerges from the mind?

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:28.100
How many people think the brain
is other than one of the

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:31.190
first two possibilities?

00:03:31.190 --> 00:03:31.540
OK.

00:03:31.540 --> 00:03:34.760
So what it amounts to is, as
soon as you ask that question,

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:37.890
what you realize is,
what is a mind?

00:03:37.890 --> 00:03:39.090
I mean--

00:03:39.090 --> 00:03:41.060
the mind is not a synapse.

00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:42.010
It's not a neuron.

00:03:42.010 --> 00:03:45.400
It's not something that you
weigh, measure, feel, pet,

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:48.530
stroke, talk, ask
questions to.

00:03:48.530 --> 00:03:48.760
OK.

00:03:48.760 --> 00:03:54.380
So what I really want to do is
talk about the brain as it

00:03:54.380 --> 00:03:58.460
generates some of our concepts
of the mind and maybe to just

00:03:58.460 --> 00:04:02.280
alter, if possible, the ways
we think about a mind.

00:04:02.280 --> 00:04:03.450
I'm not going to give
you any answers.

00:04:03.450 --> 00:04:08.780
If you think I know what the
mind is, the door's open.

00:04:08.780 --> 00:04:09.400
So--

00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:13.370
but before we do that, I want to
see one thing to Google and

00:04:13.370 --> 00:04:15.820
at the same time be the
background of this talk.

00:04:15.820 --> 00:04:19.260
This is something I
heard yesterday.

00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:20.950
And it was someone in the
locker where I work out.

00:04:20.950 --> 00:04:22.200
And he said--

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:28.930
and he said then, with a
perfectly straight face,

00:04:28.930 --> 00:04:30.480
there's so much information,
I have trouble

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:32.210
keeping up with reality.

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:38.450
And what makes this funny, to
me, is that you're confusing

00:04:38.450 --> 00:04:40.540
two concepts--

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:43.020
fact with reality.

00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:45.230
And reality is a philosophical,

00:04:45.230 --> 00:04:49.560
metaphysical conundrum.

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:53.170
It's not a scientific fact,
unless you believe that

00:04:53.170 --> 00:04:54.170
everything is objective.

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:54.660
And that's it.

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:56.630
In which case, you're still
stuck with what are abstract

00:04:56.630 --> 00:04:57.810
ideas, and so on.

00:04:57.810 --> 00:05:03.180
But the difference is you
have facts at one level.

00:05:03.180 --> 00:05:05.400
And you have ideas
at another level.

00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:07.600
And the real question in going
from the brain to the mind is,

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:09.360
can you bridge that gap?

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:12.070
So a second of background--

00:05:12.070 --> 00:05:15.190
I'm so old that I started in an
era where people believed

00:05:15.190 --> 00:05:17.890
in mind-body dualism.

00:05:17.890 --> 00:05:20.360
When I was a neurology resident,
one of the questions

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:23.750
you were commonly called on
to have to solve is, is a

00:05:23.750 --> 00:05:27.470
patient's problem psychiatric
or neurologic?

00:05:27.470 --> 00:05:29.490
As though there was
a difference.

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:32.100
Now we've gone 40 years
down the road.

00:05:32.100 --> 00:05:35.890
And technology is obviously
spectacular compared to when I

00:05:35.890 --> 00:05:37.400
first started out.

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:41.880
But there's an inherent,
underlying problem.

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:45.105
One has to translate
Neuroscience into a language

00:05:45.105 --> 00:05:47.650
that's comprehensible.

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:49.640
It doesn't mean anything
to say that synapses

00:05:49.640 --> 00:05:50.830
are firing at x-rate.

00:05:50.830 --> 00:05:55.540
You have to know what that means
in terms of experience.

00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:58.560
You have to have a language
for interpretation.

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:02.260
But the language, ironically,
of Neuroscience is the

00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:07.290
language of popular culture, of
psychology, of philosophy,

00:06:07.290 --> 00:06:08.180
movies, et cetera.

00:06:08.180 --> 00:06:10.060
So in other words, when people
start an experiment, they say,

00:06:10.060 --> 00:06:12.670
I'm going to the
study altruism.

00:06:12.670 --> 00:06:13.710
OK.

00:06:13.710 --> 00:06:15.800
That's a great idea.

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:17.670
But everybody has different
idea of altruism.

00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:20.110
Some people think it's
self-serving and other people

00:06:20.110 --> 00:06:22.750
think it's self-sacrificing.

00:06:22.750 --> 00:06:26.260
But the concept of altruism
is not written in stone

00:06:26.260 --> 00:06:30.030
somewhere, where you can study
it, get adequate data, and

00:06:30.030 --> 00:06:34.240
suddenly say that data
represents an objective fact

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:37.170
at the level of the
definition.

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:44.350
So the circular arrows I have
there are because there's

00:06:44.350 --> 00:06:49.240
become a peculiar recursive
phenomena.

00:06:49.240 --> 00:06:52.570
As philosophy wants desperately
to keep up with

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:58.440
science, it takes the facts
of Neuroscience.

00:06:58.440 --> 00:07:01.500
And as Neuroscience tries to
explain Neuroscience to the l

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:03.080
they use the language
of philosophy.

00:07:03.080 --> 00:07:05.780
So you see all these books now
on free will, for example.

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:10.300
Well, free will it's not is
not a scientific piece of

00:07:10.300 --> 00:07:10.890
information.

00:07:10.890 --> 00:07:13.160
It is a concept that originally
arose out of a

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:15.430
theologic construct.

00:07:15.430 --> 00:07:20.800
So I was just talking with Tom
a minute ago about the

00:07:20.800 --> 00:07:22.390
computational aspects
of the brain.

00:07:22.390 --> 00:07:28.060
So let's take the picture on the
left, which allegedly is a

00:07:28.060 --> 00:07:29.420
reconstructed, three
dimensional

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:33.360
picture of a pain matrix.

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:36.630
Now imagine that you have
someone who tells you that

00:07:36.630 --> 00:07:39.600
their toe hurts, and you
have that picture.

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:41.290
You say, well this corresponds
with the

00:07:41.290 --> 00:07:45.400
person's subjective phenomena.

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:47.910
Now suppose you have the same
picture, and they tell you

00:07:47.910 --> 00:07:50.780
they don't have any subjective
phenomenon.

00:07:50.780 --> 00:07:52.150
Question is, how do you
interpret that?

00:07:52.150 --> 00:07:56.280
Now there are loads of studies
on so-called neural correlates

00:07:56.280 --> 00:08:00.110
of pain, including in
unconscious animals.

00:08:00.110 --> 00:08:03.460
Now you get into a real
philosophical, psychological,

00:08:03.460 --> 00:08:08.320
or metaphysical conundrum, of
what is unconscious pain?

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:12.000
So if you believe that this
report is the neural correlate

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.860
of pain, was it mean if you see
that someone who says they

00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:15.810
don't have pain?

00:08:15.810 --> 00:08:20.360
So there are obviously some
major issues that have arisen

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:22.080
in talking about different
levels.

00:08:22.080 --> 00:08:31.290
And it's created and some
fabulous nonsense.

00:08:31.290 --> 00:08:33.830
And I'll just let you look
through these real quickly.

00:08:33.830 --> 00:08:36.150
These are all gathered
from good journals.

00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:40.590
These are not from
garbage journals.

00:08:40.590 --> 00:08:42.770
How about that one?

00:08:42.770 --> 00:08:44.900
What does it mean to have
a site for free will?

00:08:48.060 --> 00:08:51.980
And this one, I saw
this morning.

00:08:51.980 --> 00:08:54.450
And here again is the problem.
"Unrealistic Optimism in the

00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:56.830
Face of Reality" is in
Nature neuroscience

00:08:56.830 --> 00:08:58.900
article this morning.

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:01.420
Or "fMRI Proves that
Pain is Real".

00:09:01.420 --> 00:09:02.660
I mean, what else would it be?

00:09:02.660 --> 00:09:04.850
But then it gets into the
definition of what is real.

00:09:08.910 --> 00:09:11.810
This is one where they showed
a number of women some

00:09:11.810 --> 00:09:14.440
pornographic pictures, and
they weren't aroused.

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:17.010
And they found an area of the
brain didn't light up like it

00:09:17.010 --> 00:09:20.320
should in other women who were
aroused-- and therefore, the

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:21.750
conclusion, that the pain--

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:24.050
that libido problems were in
the brain, not the mind.

00:09:24.050 --> 00:09:26.360
And I'm going--

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:28.150
misunderstanding of the
difference between the brain

00:09:28.150 --> 00:09:29.680
and mind, I thought maybe that
there were people having a bad

00:09:29.680 --> 00:09:31.180
hair day or something.

00:09:31.180 --> 00:09:33.880
I mean the reasons are
infinite, but the

00:09:33.880 --> 00:09:36.550
interpretation is
reductionist.

00:09:36.550 --> 00:09:39.440
This one was particularly
spectacular.

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:42.630
The suggestion was that since
you can demonstrate neural

00:09:42.630 --> 00:09:48.440
pathways or areas of brain that
light up for courage, the

00:09:48.440 --> 00:09:51.940
theory is well maybe we can
stimulate courage through

00:09:51.940 --> 00:09:54.550
trans-cranial magnetic
stimulation.

00:09:54.550 --> 00:09:58.520
But the one that really
stopped me was--

00:09:58.520 --> 00:09:59.890
a couple weeks ago,
this one came out.

00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:06.260
Now does anybody think that a
baby five months old doesn't

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:09.230
have memory and consciousness?

00:10:09.230 --> 00:10:14.020
Francis Crick once said a study
not worth is doing well.

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:19.850
But nevertheless, this is what
happens when you're trying to

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:22.420
prove something beyond
the area of data.

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:25.700
If they had said, we have seen
a certain neural activity

00:10:25.700 --> 00:10:29.815
associated with babies at this
level of neural development,

00:10:29.815 --> 00:10:31.390
hey, that's great!

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:32.940
Data is data.

00:10:32.940 --> 00:10:35.580
The interpretation is
storytelling, which is really

00:10:35.580 --> 00:10:38.230
going to be the punchline
of my little talk today.

00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:40.840
But it's not just humorous.

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:45.790
It's changing our attitude in
ways that are fundamental and

00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:46.600
kind of alarming.

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:51.670
So I want to actually present
a clinical case to you folks

00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:53.665
and ask you to make
the diagnosis.

00:10:56.420 --> 00:10:58.910
As you do, think about why
you came up with the

00:10:58.910 --> 00:11:01.050
ideas that you did.

00:11:01.050 --> 00:11:04.510
Keep in mind that one of the
real advantages of the Oliver

00:11:04.510 --> 00:11:10.770
Sacks method of neurology is in
observing the patient and

00:11:10.770 --> 00:11:15.600
talking to them and get the
steps that lead up to whatever

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:19.230
ideas or that emerges.

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:22.810
So the case was very simple, was
a young 25-year-old woman

00:11:22.810 --> 00:11:25.240
who was in a massive automobile
accident,

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:28.460
unfortunately had devastating
brain damage.

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:33.820
She was left in what's called a
persistent vegetative state.

00:11:33.820 --> 00:11:37.730
She would open your eyes but
did not look around, didn't

00:11:37.730 --> 00:11:41.670
register, didn't respond, had
normal wake-sleep cycles, but

00:11:41.670 --> 00:11:45.000
essentially had no response to
her outside environment.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.350
And the regular MRI scan
showed massive

00:11:47.350 --> 00:11:48.700
areas of brain damage.

00:11:48.700 --> 00:11:50.670
But not all of her
cortex was--

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:53.400
there were preserved areas of
cortex and other areas that

00:11:53.400 --> 00:11:56.180
were greatly damaged.

00:11:56.180 --> 00:12:01.740
Well at the researchers did a
wonderful, technologically

00:12:01.740 --> 00:12:04.280
sophisticated study.

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:08.340
They put that they put
headphones on her, put her

00:12:08.340 --> 00:12:12.240
inside an fMRI scanner, and
asked her two questions.

00:12:12.240 --> 00:12:17.450
One, can you imagine walking
around your house?

00:12:17.450 --> 00:12:20.320
And number two, can you imagine
playing tennis?

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:22.680
And she had been an avid
tennis player before.

00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:29.570
Now they then compared her fMRI
scan to normal controls.

00:12:29.570 --> 00:12:33.630
And they were quite similar,
given variances fMRIs.

00:12:33.630 --> 00:12:35.010
They were basically the same.

00:12:35.010 --> 00:12:38.680
So her brain lit up
the same way as

00:12:38.680 --> 00:12:41.860
normal, healthy controls.

00:12:41.860 --> 00:12:43.880
How many of you people
would think that

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:45.130
she's therefore conscious?

00:12:48.848 --> 00:12:51.190
OK.

00:12:51.190 --> 00:12:53.270
Now let me say that she's
still lying there

00:12:53.270 --> 00:12:53.990
unresponsive.

00:12:53.990 --> 00:12:56.510
And now what we're left with
is a definition of

00:12:56.510 --> 00:12:57.810
consciousness.

00:12:57.810 --> 00:13:00.470
And how do you figure out what
represents consciousness?

00:13:00.470 --> 00:13:03.270
Now I'm going to put aside that
consciousness can be a

00:13:03.270 --> 00:13:05.440
variety of states from nightmare
to delirium to

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:08.320
confusion to they kind of
confusion you have when you

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:10.550
first awaken in the morning,
but you're still awake and

00:13:10.550 --> 00:13:13.080
conscious, but you're
fuzzy in the head.

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:15.250
So there are lots of subjective
states of

00:13:15.250 --> 00:13:16.610
consciousness, not just one.

00:13:16.610 --> 00:13:18.000
It's not binary.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:19.530
And there's also the
problem of arousal.

00:13:19.530 --> 00:13:21.370
But put that aside
for the moment.

00:13:21.370 --> 00:13:26.190
And then so you start to think
about, well, how much did you

00:13:26.190 --> 00:13:30.580
bring to unconsciously versus
when do you know it was

00:13:30.580 --> 00:13:31.750
consciously done?

00:13:31.750 --> 00:13:33.390
So there are two aspects
to that question.

00:13:33.390 --> 00:13:36.360
So the first is, we know that if
you're at a cocktail party

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:38.150
and you hear your name
mentioned, even though you

00:13:38.150 --> 00:13:40.000
weren't listening, suddenly
you become aware of

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.950
conversation that you hadn't
heard earlier.

00:13:42.950 --> 00:13:48.420
Well I've done lots of studies
that have shown that you can

00:13:48.420 --> 00:13:52.785
process auditory and visual
information even when you're

00:13:52.785 --> 00:13:54.110
unresponsive.

00:13:54.110 --> 00:13:58.410
For example, on the lower end of
the scale, when mothers are

00:13:58.410 --> 00:14:02.020
sleeping and you present a
bunch of names to them,

00:14:02.020 --> 00:14:02.680
nothing happens.

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:04.650
You present the name of the
child, even though they don't

00:14:04.650 --> 00:14:06.770
wake up, their EEG changes.

00:14:06.770 --> 00:14:10.820
You can present people in coma
visual representations of

00:14:10.820 --> 00:14:15.540
their family, and their brains
and cortical areas that are

00:14:15.540 --> 00:14:18.820
lower levels than the total
cortical area will light up.

00:14:18.820 --> 00:14:22.480
So what you're left with is a
fundamental question that has

00:14:22.480 --> 00:14:23.860
not yet been answered.

00:14:23.860 --> 00:14:25.330
I'm not even sure it's
addressable.

00:14:25.330 --> 00:14:28.540
But it certainly hasn't been
answered is, how much of our

00:14:28.540 --> 00:14:30.720
thought conscious?

00:14:30.720 --> 00:14:34.900
And how much of our thought
actually is unconscious?

00:14:34.900 --> 00:14:37.790
Then the question arises, in
this day and age, what would

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:39.760
you say to the family?

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:46.370
So here's what the authors said
in their article and said

00:14:46.370 --> 00:14:47.620
the family.

00:14:49.970 --> 00:14:52.700
And my question is that the
correct approach to modern

00:14:52.700 --> 00:14:54.600
Neuroscience?

00:14:54.600 --> 00:14:57.470
Would that be-- how many people
would vote that that is

00:14:57.470 --> 00:14:58.860
what they should tell
the family?

00:15:01.480 --> 00:15:05.020
Wouldn't it make more sense to
say, we see that she still

00:15:05.020 --> 00:15:08.720
clinically unresponsive,
statistics in this group

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:12.530
patients is the recovery
is relatively limited.

00:15:12.530 --> 00:15:14.430
But on the other hand, we have
this new information and it

00:15:14.430 --> 00:15:15.750
may shed additional
light on this.

00:15:15.750 --> 00:15:16.800
And we need to follow this up.

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:17.520
We need more.

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:21.150
We need to consider this.

00:15:21.150 --> 00:15:25.180
But then what you realize is
what we're really down to is

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:27.680
again the problem
of definition.

00:15:27.680 --> 00:15:30.410
So let me ask you a question,
how many people in this room

00:15:30.410 --> 00:15:33.110
think you have complex,
conscious thought?

00:15:36.020 --> 00:15:37.600
OK.

00:15:37.600 --> 00:15:41.520
So let me just try and dissuade
you of that one.

00:15:46.190 --> 00:15:50.350
The average the average person,
even at Google--

00:15:50.350 --> 00:15:53.410
so average for Google, which
maybe you shift the Bell Curve

00:15:53.410 --> 00:15:57.190
over 52 IQ points, whatever,
still can only remember seven

00:15:57.190 --> 00:15:59.780
to nine digits.

00:15:59.780 --> 00:16:06.440
Still if you take a complex
telephone number, you chunk it

00:16:06.440 --> 00:16:09.240
into the area code, prefix,
suffix, et cetera.

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:15.600
We can only remember about four
chunks of information at

00:16:15.600 --> 00:16:17.550
one time, at one time.

00:16:20.190 --> 00:16:23.370
And that lasts for a minute or
two, so-called short term or

00:16:23.370 --> 00:16:24.650
working memory.

00:16:24.650 --> 00:16:27.300
That's all you could
do consciously.

00:16:27.300 --> 00:16:30.570
You have the RAM of the first
computers ever made.

00:16:30.570 --> 00:16:33.440
And I mean, itty bitty.

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:35.240
Now if you have a--

00:16:35.240 --> 00:16:39.090
trying to do a complex thought
that involves, let's say,

00:16:39.090 --> 00:16:46.510
myriad factors, let's say like
global climate change.

00:16:46.510 --> 00:16:49.450
Now you come up with four or
five factors, like you got to

00:16:49.450 --> 00:16:55.630
invest in Greenland
or the role of

00:16:55.630 --> 00:16:57.500
polar bear or whatever.

00:16:57.500 --> 00:17:00.770
Then suddenly somebody gives you
another set of five, you

00:17:00.770 --> 00:17:03.990
can't keep those five in along
with the other four.

00:17:03.990 --> 00:17:05.380
So it's like having an--

00:17:05.380 --> 00:17:07.220
what do they call those?

00:17:07.220 --> 00:17:08.069
Etch-a-Sketch?

00:17:08.069 --> 00:17:13.450
Where you have to erase or store
that memory, in order to

00:17:13.450 --> 00:17:16.210
put more in-- your random
access memory

00:17:16.210 --> 00:17:18.349
of short term memory.

00:17:18.349 --> 00:17:21.339
Once it's in your unconscious,
it's subject to every single

00:17:21.339 --> 00:17:24.119
bias that your unconscious
brain has.

00:17:24.119 --> 00:17:27.380
And you don't need for me to
tell you that that's the

00:17:27.380 --> 00:17:28.150
subject of everything--

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:29.250
Daniel Kahneman books.

00:17:29.250 --> 00:17:33.240
I mean, it's everywhere we are
understanding the biases of

00:17:33.240 --> 00:17:34.120
the unconscious.

00:17:34.120 --> 00:17:39.250
So what it amounts to-- once
you're down in outside of

00:17:39.250 --> 00:17:41.110
awareness--

00:17:41.110 --> 00:17:44.020
If a Blue Jay flies over here,
it may change my idea about

00:17:44.020 --> 00:17:47.230
what is global warming,
for example.

00:17:47.230 --> 00:17:47.780
OK.

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:50.270
Now let me ask the same question
again, how many of

00:17:50.270 --> 00:17:53.470
you people believe in complex,
conscious thought?

00:17:53.470 --> 00:17:55.110
It doesn't change anything
what I tell you.

00:17:55.110 --> 00:17:57.050
And that's really
what I wanted--

00:17:57.050 --> 00:17:58.450
this is what of this is
going to be about.

00:17:58.450 --> 00:18:00.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:04.370
Something's wrong because we
know-- we all feel that.

00:18:04.370 --> 00:18:05.620
OK.

00:18:07.990 --> 00:18:10.150
Some years ago, I wrote a book
--five years ago-- a book

00:18:10.150 --> 00:18:11.850
called "On Being Certain".

00:18:11.850 --> 00:18:16.950
And in it, what I finally
realized is that, in addition

00:18:16.950 --> 00:18:21.270
to having the computational
skills of your brain, your

00:18:21.270 --> 00:18:23.760
brain has to notify yourself
what's going

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:26.230
on outside of awareness.

00:18:26.230 --> 00:18:27.575
So you take for example--

00:18:31.400 --> 00:18:33.350
I look out at faces.

00:18:33.350 --> 00:18:34.990
Now, I don't recognize
most of you.

00:18:34.990 --> 00:18:37.200
But I recognize that
you're all people.

00:18:37.200 --> 00:18:38.970
I mean it that much--
or mostly.

00:18:41.550 --> 00:18:45.050
That's a pattern recognition
that's going unconsciously.

00:18:45.050 --> 00:18:48.030
But I don't have any sense
of recognition.

00:18:48.030 --> 00:18:51.570
But if I recognize somebody
sitting in the front row,

00:18:51.570 --> 00:18:53.600
let's say, I will also--

00:18:53.600 --> 00:18:56.690
my brain, if it wants to draw
attention to it, will say,

00:18:56.690 --> 00:18:59.950
that's Peter Norvig,
let's say.

00:18:59.950 --> 00:19:04.790
So you if you think about
it, we have systems for

00:19:04.790 --> 00:19:06.530
understanding ourselves
in our environment.

00:19:06.530 --> 00:19:09.160
That's sight, sound, so on.

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:13.440
We have somatic sensations
for the external world.

00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:17.370
We have visceral sensations
for internal world.

00:19:17.370 --> 00:19:20.450
But we obviously must have
some kind of subjective

00:19:20.450 --> 00:19:23.200
sensation for what goes
on computationally.

00:19:23.200 --> 00:19:24.370
It just doesn't go on--

00:19:24.370 --> 00:19:26.760
it goes on in silence,
the computation.

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:27.775
But then you have
to be notified.

00:19:27.775 --> 00:19:30.370
If there's 3% chance that I
recognize someone in the

00:19:30.370 --> 00:19:32.530
audience, maybe it doesn't
reach the threshold.

00:19:32.530 --> 00:19:33.390
I don't notice it.

00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:36.280
It reaches 60% as
a competition.

00:19:36.280 --> 00:19:37.930
Not only do you get
the computation.

00:19:37.930 --> 00:19:38.490
But you get a message.

00:19:38.490 --> 00:19:41.530
The Message says, I recognize
that person.

00:19:41.530 --> 00:19:44.680
And then at 100%, you say that's
absolutely Joe Blow.

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:48.540
And the same kind of idea
goes for thought.

00:19:48.540 --> 00:19:51.440
If you have a hunch, and it's
such a low level that you

00:19:51.440 --> 00:19:52.440
don't pay attention to it.

00:19:52.440 --> 00:19:53.110
Then you say, I don't know.

00:19:53.110 --> 00:19:53.900
That might be right.

00:19:53.900 --> 00:19:54.680
That's worth pursuing.

00:19:54.680 --> 00:19:57.950
Oh, um, to an ah ha, which
is an absolute certainty.

00:19:57.950 --> 00:20:02.180
But nobody here can
generate an ah ha.

00:20:02.180 --> 00:20:04.105
An ah ha happens to you.

00:20:04.105 --> 00:20:05.740
It is a sensation.

00:20:05.740 --> 00:20:07.860
It is the same thing as an itch
or a pain, only it's a

00:20:07.860 --> 00:20:09.680
glorious sensation.

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:14.360
So what finally occurred to me
is that we have a number of

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:20.270
involuntary mental sensations
that generate much of what we

00:20:20.270 --> 00:20:21.260
experience is a mind.

00:20:21.260 --> 00:20:26.480
Let's put aside emotions and
moods and a small amount

00:20:26.480 --> 00:20:28.680
memory that we can have
in random access.

00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:31.780
But when I asked you the
question about how many people

00:20:31.780 --> 00:20:33.920
think you still complex
conscious thought.

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:36.900
The question is why?

00:20:36.900 --> 00:20:39.410
Because we experience it.

00:20:39.410 --> 00:20:40.530
So we're having an experience.

00:20:40.530 --> 00:20:41.490
So let me ask you--

00:20:41.490 --> 00:20:43.270
put it another way.

00:20:43.270 --> 00:20:48.340
What if you go to bed at night,
and you're trying to

00:20:48.340 --> 00:20:52.030
remember Charlie Brown's name,
and you can't remember it.

00:20:52.030 --> 00:20:54.810
Wake up in the morning,
and you remember it.

00:20:54.810 --> 00:20:55.990
And you say, it just
occurred me.

00:20:55.990 --> 00:20:58.240
It popped into my mind,
whatever you say.

00:20:58.240 --> 00:21:01.710
You have no sensation of
thinking, is that correct?

00:21:01.710 --> 00:21:02.640
It just occurs to you.

00:21:02.640 --> 00:21:06.220
That's why people talk about
muses and so on.

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:09.690
But if you try really hard to
remember Charlie Brown's name,

00:21:09.690 --> 00:21:12.180
you have a sense of effort.

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:15.850
You have a sense that you're
thinking about it.

00:21:15.850 --> 00:21:17.930
So the real question is, is
brain working differently

00:21:17.930 --> 00:21:19.700
under those two circumstances?

00:21:19.700 --> 00:21:22.180
And how would you know?

00:21:22.180 --> 00:21:25.410
It seems unlikely that your
heart beats differently when

00:21:25.410 --> 00:21:28.260
you feel it beating than
if and when you don't.

00:21:28.260 --> 00:21:30.390
By the same token, it seems
unlikely that your brain would

00:21:30.390 --> 00:21:32.730
have a mechanism where it
switches back and forth.

00:21:32.730 --> 00:21:34.740
If you're aware of it,
it works in one way.

00:21:34.740 --> 00:21:36.520
And if you're not aware of
it, it works completely

00:21:36.520 --> 00:21:37.840
differently.

00:21:37.840 --> 00:21:39.360
So what's the difference?

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:42.040
The difference is the way
you feel about it.

00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:45.340
So if you're trying to study a
really hard calculus problem,

00:21:45.340 --> 00:21:48.030
and you feel like you're
putting a lot

00:21:48.030 --> 00:21:49.890
of effort into it.

00:21:49.890 --> 00:21:51.520
So you say, I study
really hard.

00:21:51.520 --> 00:21:53.710
I thought really hard
about that.

00:21:53.710 --> 00:21:55.300
But suppose you wake up in the
morning with the answer to

00:21:55.300 --> 00:21:58.300
that problem, you don't have
any sense of effort at all.

00:21:58.300 --> 00:21:58.910
None.

00:21:58.910 --> 00:22:02.020
So if you go back to the diagram
previously about

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:06.390
little, small nubbin of purely
conscious thought, but it's

00:22:06.390 --> 00:22:08.260
all we experience.

00:22:08.260 --> 00:22:10.965
That's how we think we all
have conscious, complex

00:22:10.965 --> 00:22:13.590
thought, irrespective
of what you might

00:22:13.590 --> 00:22:15.203
surmise from the data.

00:22:15.203 --> 00:22:16.030
OK?

00:22:16.030 --> 00:22:19.010
And my one point is they
are different.

00:22:19.010 --> 00:22:21.570
There are the sensory
phenomena.

00:22:21.570 --> 00:22:22.750
And there are the
computations.

00:22:22.750 --> 00:22:26.110
And just as an aside, for those
people who are of the

00:22:26.110 --> 00:22:29.050
old school and have studied
the Chinese box experiment

00:22:29.050 --> 00:22:32.040
about whether AI has--

00:22:32.040 --> 00:22:37.000
whether a computer can really
understand, is a confusion

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:40.540
about the difference between
computation and sensation.

00:22:40.540 --> 00:22:44.730
Computers do really great
at whatever they do.

00:22:44.730 --> 00:22:47.970
It's in the semantics of
understanding that they don't

00:22:47.970 --> 00:22:50.760
have the sensory phenomena
that gives us a sense of

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:51.160
understanding.

00:22:51.160 --> 00:22:53.600
But they may come up with
the same net result.

00:22:53.600 --> 00:22:55.160
And it may well surpass us.

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:57.190
So you have two aspects.

00:22:57.190 --> 00:22:59.840
If you think about AI,
that's computation.

00:22:59.840 --> 00:23:02.570
If you think that the future
of AI, if you want to make

00:23:02.570 --> 00:23:07.030
true robots are human beings,
you'll have figure out what

00:23:07.030 --> 00:23:08.250
the sensory phenomena are.

00:23:08.250 --> 00:23:11.400
And that's really the hard
problem of consciousness.

00:23:11.400 --> 00:23:13.360
Whether we can ever
get there--

00:23:13.360 --> 00:23:14.720
you can debate about that.

00:23:14.720 --> 00:23:16.140
But unless you're clairvoyant,
I can't tell you

00:23:16.140 --> 00:23:18.410
which is more likely.

00:23:18.410 --> 00:23:23.710
So if you think about it, it's
not just pattern recognition

00:23:23.710 --> 00:23:25.330
equals recognition sensation.

00:23:25.330 --> 00:23:28.440
But there are a whole
host of sensations.

00:23:28.440 --> 00:23:30.720
Feeling and knowing,
I just mentioned.

00:23:30.720 --> 00:23:34.000
What I'd like to just start
with something that we all

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:37.080
know but kind of deny.

00:23:37.080 --> 00:23:41.720
We have physical dimensions
of a sense of self.

00:23:41.720 --> 00:23:44.050
For example, if I stimulate a
certain area of the brain, I

00:23:44.050 --> 00:23:45.380
can create out of
body sensations.

00:23:48.200 --> 00:23:50.240
This can happen with people
with brain tumors, with

00:23:50.240 --> 00:23:51.530
certain forms epilepsy.

00:23:51.530 --> 00:23:54.740
What it amounts to those we
can actually, with virtual

00:23:54.740 --> 00:23:59.420
reality, shift one's own
personal sense of self.

00:23:59.420 --> 00:24:03.340
Because our sense of self comes
from our lives, in terms

00:24:03.340 --> 00:24:04.700
of where we think
we're located.

00:24:04.700 --> 00:24:07.810
So if you look out at the world,
you're seeing it from

00:24:07.810 --> 00:24:09.350
wherever perspective
of your eye.

00:24:09.350 --> 00:24:13.680
Now if I put a virtual reality
apparatus on your eyes, but

00:24:13.680 --> 00:24:15.840
then have the camera start from
a different position,

00:24:15.840 --> 00:24:20.170
like from the vantage point of
a nearby mannequin, people

00:24:20.170 --> 00:24:23.910
will feel that they are located
inside the mannequin.

00:24:23.910 --> 00:24:26.580
And then you can come up to that
mannequin with a knife

00:24:26.580 --> 00:24:28.060
and try and stab
the mannequin.

00:24:28.060 --> 00:24:30.250
And the person will actually
experience increased heart

00:24:30.250 --> 00:24:32.470
rate, sweating, and a feeling
of anxiety because he

00:24:32.470 --> 00:24:35.150
actually-- even though he
knows, cognitively, that

00:24:35.150 --> 00:24:37.600
that's not him, he can't control
the feeling that he's

00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:39.150
actually inside the mannequin.

00:24:39.150 --> 00:24:42.920
So these body swap illusion's
clearly tell you that the

00:24:42.920 --> 00:24:45.515
brain creates a physical
sense of self.

00:24:45.515 --> 00:24:48.940
It's an involuntary sensation.

00:24:48.940 --> 00:24:52.080
Also creates a sense
of ownership--

00:24:52.080 --> 00:24:56.830
and by ownership, I mean, if you
raise your arm like this

00:24:56.830 --> 00:24:59.310
you feel like you've done
it voluntarily and

00:24:59.310 --> 00:25:00.850
that it's your arm.

00:25:00.850 --> 00:25:02.970
If you go to a doctor's office,
and he raises your

00:25:02.970 --> 00:25:04.850
arm, it's still your arm.

00:25:04.850 --> 00:25:06.480
But you no long feel that
you did it yourself.

00:25:06.480 --> 00:25:12.924
We have very good body
part recognition.

00:25:12.924 --> 00:25:16.800
If we have good recognition for
our body parts, then we

00:25:16.800 --> 00:25:19.810
also have a sense of ownership
of our mind.

00:25:19.810 --> 00:25:21.730
It's my mind.

00:25:21.730 --> 00:25:24.450
And these are my thoughts.

00:25:24.450 --> 00:25:26.410
We can't get away from the
fact and when we have a

00:25:26.410 --> 00:25:28.780
thought, we thought we thought
it, because of the feelings.

00:25:28.780 --> 00:25:30.990
We can have a feeling that
since we have a sense of

00:25:30.990 --> 00:25:35.010
agency that we generated the
thought, and that a sense of

00:25:35.010 --> 00:25:39.720
agency is part of what makes
Thought A feel like it

00:25:39.720 --> 00:25:42.310
generates Thought B.

00:25:42.310 --> 00:25:48.100
Now it's hard to say this and
fully accept this because all

00:25:48.100 --> 00:25:50.830
we experience is Thought A
causes Thought B. So even

00:25:50.830 --> 00:25:54.960
while I'm talking to you here, I
believe that I'm making some

00:25:54.960 --> 00:26:01.700
clever set sentences following
a linear fashion But if you

00:26:01.700 --> 00:26:05.380
think about it, the brain
works in parallel.

00:26:05.380 --> 00:26:07.820
Myriad things going
on simultaneously.

00:26:07.820 --> 00:26:11.550
So Mike's sensation of a linear
thought may actually be

00:26:11.550 --> 00:26:15.540
a misrepresentation, what
is occurring at

00:26:15.540 --> 00:26:16.920
an unconscious level.

00:26:16.920 --> 00:26:17.680
But let me go on.

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:21.860
So if you have a sense of
ownership of your body parts

00:26:21.860 --> 00:26:24.490
and a constrained
physical self--

00:26:24.490 --> 00:26:27.420
they've even shown, for example,
that if you have

00:26:27.420 --> 00:26:32.315
damage to your amygdala, it will
change how close you can

00:26:32.315 --> 00:26:33.150
get to other people.

00:26:33.150 --> 00:26:35.500
If you have damage to you
amygdala, instead-- our normal

00:26:35.500 --> 00:26:38.650
interpersonal distance of other
people's a few feet.

00:26:38.650 --> 00:26:40.540
People who have these
damaged--

00:26:40.540 --> 00:26:45.420
they have no sense
of restriction.

