we should take out the pancreas
of a stray dog, so we

00:39:41.800 --> 00:39:45.870
could watch how it suffered when
it died from diabetes.

00:39:45.870 --> 00:39:48.740
And nobody even considered the
fact that they were taking a

00:39:48.740 --> 00:39:49.490
dog and doing it.

00:39:49.490 --> 00:39:50.740
I still have nightmares
about that.

00:39:54.660 --> 00:40:00.500
Even today though, some of the
best Neuroscientists, people I

00:40:00.500 --> 00:40:04.160
really respect, are writing
books about the science behind

00:40:04.160 --> 00:40:06.160
what makes us unique.

00:40:06.160 --> 00:40:08.760
Now we think we're unique
because we have these feelings

00:40:08.760 --> 00:40:09.930
of uniqueness.

00:40:09.930 --> 00:40:13.360
So it's ironically it's our
biology dictates our sense of

00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:14.590
uniqueness.

00:40:14.590 --> 00:40:17.170
The feeling tells us
that we're unique.

00:40:17.170 --> 00:40:21.140
But hey, that's no different
with Sarah Palin says.

00:40:21.140 --> 00:40:22.750
It's the same argument.

00:40:22.750 --> 00:40:25.860
And certainly, at some point,
we should start to consider

00:40:25.860 --> 00:40:28.870
what these involuntary
sensations mean towards our

00:40:28.870 --> 00:40:31.046
public policy, et cetera.

00:40:31.046 --> 00:40:34.910
And now on that not let me just
say that five years ago,

00:40:34.910 --> 00:40:38.350
I gave you talk on
my last book.

00:40:38.350 --> 00:40:40.280
And I showed this slide.

00:40:40.280 --> 00:40:44.910
And I smugly said, this is an
example of how we feel that

00:40:44.910 --> 00:40:49.640
top slide is longer than
the bottom slide.

00:40:49.640 --> 00:40:52.350
And I said, this is an example
of how we have a feeling of

00:40:52.350 --> 00:40:53.570
knowing which is involuntary.

00:40:53.570 --> 00:40:55.350
Even I tell you the slide--

00:40:55.350 --> 00:40:59.060
the two lengths are the same.

00:40:59.060 --> 00:41:00.270
We still feel the other one.

00:41:00.270 --> 00:41:04.520
So it's a feeling of knowing
at odds with our cognitive

00:41:04.520 --> 00:41:05.470
understanding.

00:41:05.470 --> 00:41:06.940
And I thought wasn't
that clever.

00:41:06.940 --> 00:41:12.640
But what I didn't realize is
that this isn't just a matter

00:41:12.640 --> 00:41:15.630
of our brains in the abstract.

00:41:15.630 --> 00:41:18.130
They've done studies now, which
came out within a year

00:41:18.130 --> 00:41:20.940
or two ago, that they gave the
same pictures to different

00:41:20.940 --> 00:41:22.670
kinds of cultures.

00:41:22.670 --> 00:41:26.250
From the so-called Western
technology, highly educated

00:41:26.250 --> 00:41:33.980
kids, to tribes in Africa.

00:41:33.980 --> 00:41:37.140
Tribes in Africa don't
see a difference.

00:41:37.140 --> 00:41:39.380
They see no illusion
here whatsoever.

00:41:39.380 --> 00:41:41.740
And they've tried this
with other things.

00:41:41.740 --> 00:41:45.710
And the conclusion of the
authors is that something as

00:41:45.710 --> 00:41:50.840
basic as our visual perception
can be changed by our culture.

00:41:50.840 --> 00:41:52.970
So you go back, you think
about the locust,

00:41:52.970 --> 00:41:54.330
you think on this.

00:41:54.330 --> 00:42:00.002
We need to rethink how
Neuroscience thinks about the

00:42:00.002 --> 00:42:01.180
mind, not the brain.

00:42:01.180 --> 00:42:03.490
You can study the
brain without--

00:42:03.490 --> 00:42:05.110
that's pure science.

00:42:07.640 --> 00:42:09.340
So I just--

00:42:09.340 --> 00:42:12.470
so I leave some time for
questions, I want to emphasize

00:42:12.470 --> 00:42:15.880
the study the brain
as pure science.

00:42:15.880 --> 00:42:17.280
I've no qualms with
that whatsoever.

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:19.700
And there's no other way of
studying the world from the

00:42:19.700 --> 00:42:23.340
point of view of facts.

00:42:23.340 --> 00:42:25.950
But conclusions about what the
mind is are storytelling.

00:42:25.950 --> 00:42:29.600
I can give you an argument that
we have a group mind.

00:42:29.600 --> 00:42:31.700
I can tell you that
we don't have one.

00:42:31.700 --> 00:42:33.835
But I don't have any evidence
to support that.

00:42:33.835 --> 00:42:35.650
That's pure speculation.

00:42:35.650 --> 00:42:36.750
I can tell you we're unique.

00:42:36.750 --> 00:42:37.870
We're not unique.

00:42:37.870 --> 00:42:39.710
I could tell you we're
studying altruism.

00:42:39.710 --> 00:42:43.580
Those are stories that you're
telling based upon the data.

00:42:43.580 --> 00:42:47.400
And so it's from my point, the
science of the mind is one set

00:42:47.400 --> 00:42:50.400
of stories among many.

00:42:50.400 --> 00:42:51.760
Science uses data.

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:53.310
Stories use plot
and character.

00:42:53.310 --> 00:42:57.940
And all I want to share
something with you.

00:42:57.940 --> 00:43:00.440
How many people think we all
know what this lovely young

00:43:00.440 --> 00:43:02.070
lady is thinking through
Neuroscience?

00:43:05.130 --> 00:43:08.150
Wouldn't it be great to be a
mind reader, to know what

00:43:08.150 --> 00:43:08.700
animals are thinking?

00:43:08.700 --> 00:43:12.020
But the fact of matter is if
you realize that we have to

00:43:12.020 --> 00:43:17.610
have perfect understanding
what's going on in her brain,

00:43:17.610 --> 00:43:20.020
and that she's got to
be able to tell us.

00:43:20.020 --> 00:43:21.620
So--

00:43:21.620 --> 00:43:23.300
But there are other ways.

00:43:23.300 --> 00:43:26.450
In writing my books, I've
been kind of ignorant of

00:43:26.450 --> 00:43:28.110
what came before me.

00:43:28.110 --> 00:43:30.520
And I thought I'd
close with this.

00:43:30.520 --> 00:43:34.450
Aristotle said, "Our desires
harbor a hidden judgment that

00:43:34.450 --> 00:43:37.790
their ends are good." Basically,
2,500 years ago, he

00:43:37.790 --> 00:43:43.000
was telling us that our
unconscious mind also is

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:45.290
making unconscious judgments,
such as

00:43:45.290 --> 00:43:47.960
the feeling of knowing.

00:43:47.960 --> 00:43:51.230
And Dostoevsky was commenting
on conscious versus

00:43:51.230 --> 00:43:53.230
unconscious though.

00:43:53.230 --> 00:43:57.760
"Soon he sank in the deep
thought, or accurately

00:43:57.760 --> 00:44:01.600
speaking, into a complete
blindness of mind." This is

00:44:01.600 --> 00:44:05.540
written in the 1860."

00:44:05.540 --> 00:44:08.140
And for those of you who would
like to debate the free will

00:44:08.140 --> 00:44:11.370
issue, I think Tolstoy
summed this up.

00:44:11.370 --> 00:44:12.790
"You say I'm not free.

00:44:12.790 --> 00:44:14.460
But I've raised and
lowered my arm.

00:44:14.460 --> 00:44:17.000
Everybody understands that
this logical answer is

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:20.900
irrefutable proof of freedom."
He understands the paradoxical

00:44:20.900 --> 00:44:24.640
nature of any discussion
about free will.

00:44:24.640 --> 00:44:27.960
And as far as so-called
group mind.

00:44:27.960 --> 00:44:32.640
I'll leave you Charles
Bukowski's idea "If you could

00:44:32.640 --> 00:44:35.200
separate what the public thinks
from reality, that's

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:38.490
all you need to know
to bet wisely."

00:44:38.490 --> 00:44:42.550
And I think this is the state
of Neuroscience at present.

00:44:42.550 --> 00:44:48.062
So I will now answer questions
or look stupid as best I can.

00:44:48.062 --> 00:44:55.140
[APPLAUSE]

00:44:55.140 --> 00:44:58.220
AUDIENCE: If you could take
that slider that had that

00:44:58.220 --> 00:45:02.630
sense of uncertainty about and
adjust it for you just once,

00:45:02.630 --> 00:45:05.440
you only have one opportunity
to do this, how

00:45:05.440 --> 00:45:07.160
would you do it?

00:45:07.160 --> 00:45:11.290
Would you be more sure of your
inferences or less sure?

00:45:11.290 --> 00:45:12.430
ROBERT BURTON: More
sure of my--

00:45:12.430 --> 00:45:14.480
AUDIENCE: More sure of your
inferences and your thoughts

00:45:14.480 --> 00:45:17.780
and ideas and you
come up or less?

00:45:17.780 --> 00:45:21.270
ROBERT BURTON: I think that if
you don't have some certainly,

00:45:21.270 --> 00:45:23.850
at least, to the extent of
feeling you got a hunch,

00:45:23.850 --> 00:45:24.820
you're never going
to do anything.

00:45:24.820 --> 00:45:25.820
You're not going to
write a novel.

00:45:25.820 --> 00:45:26.880
Like, I've written
several novels.

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:30.120
You've have to think, I'm
on the right track.

00:45:30.120 --> 00:45:34.120
But you can have so much
uncertainty that you think

00:45:34.120 --> 00:45:37.430
that character has to do A or
B and can't do C, D, or

00:45:37.430 --> 00:45:39.028
F, you follow me?

00:45:39.028 --> 00:45:40.860
So it's--

00:45:40.860 --> 00:45:43.760
You need the middle road.

00:45:43.760 --> 00:45:44.160
How's that?

00:45:44.160 --> 00:45:45.510
That's a simple way
of putting it.

00:45:45.510 --> 00:45:47.160
AUDIENCE: That's just
copping out.

00:45:47.160 --> 00:45:47.550
ROBERT BURTON: I know.

00:45:47.550 --> 00:45:51.720
I think you have to
wear two hats.

00:45:51.720 --> 00:45:54.460
You wear an editor and
a non editor hat.

00:45:54.460 --> 00:45:59.290
In other words, when I'm writing
fiction, I say, leave

00:45:59.290 --> 00:46:01.890
the editor at home.

00:46:01.890 --> 00:46:03.880
Try everything.

00:46:03.880 --> 00:46:06.070
And then I'm going to go back
and visit with my editor's hat

00:46:06.070 --> 00:46:07.240
on and see if it makes sense.

00:46:07.240 --> 00:46:11.710
So I take no certainty is the
default position for trying to

00:46:11.710 --> 00:46:12.780
create ideas.

00:46:12.780 --> 00:46:18.930
And then as much as I can do
certainty to try disprove

00:46:18.930 --> 00:46:20.040
actually what I've written.

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:23.180
AUDIENCE: So you want control
of the slider all the time.

00:46:23.180 --> 00:46:23.440
ROBERT BURTON: No.

00:46:23.440 --> 00:46:27.740
I want it on off for a while and
then go back and reach for

00:46:27.740 --> 00:46:29.350
it if I can.

00:46:29.350 --> 00:46:30.680
But you can't do that either.

00:46:30.680 --> 00:46:31.890
I know that.

00:46:31.890 --> 00:46:33.270
You asked a tough question.

00:46:33.270 --> 00:46:33.930
You guys all do.

00:46:33.930 --> 00:46:35.280
So go ahead.

00:46:35.280 --> 00:46:38.250
AUDIENCE: What is your attitude
towards the unknown,

00:46:38.250 --> 00:46:41.190
for which we don't have the
tools currently to understand

00:46:41.190 --> 00:46:43.670
within a scientific framework.

00:46:43.670 --> 00:46:44.830
ROBERT BURTON: Couple things.

00:46:44.830 --> 00:46:48.440
One is, that if I had an answer
for you, I would be

00:46:48.440 --> 00:46:49.930
clairvoyant.

00:46:49.930 --> 00:46:52.550
By very definition, those people
who say, I think in '50

00:46:52.550 --> 00:46:55.890
years or 20 years or 10 years or
next week or sometime we're

00:46:55.890 --> 00:46:58.320
going to understand the mind,
they're making a prediction

00:46:58.320 --> 00:47:02.130
based upon clairvoyance,
not facts.

00:47:02.130 --> 00:47:04.790
And if I told you we weren't,
I would also be

00:47:04.790 --> 00:47:05.970
basing it on no facts.

00:47:05.970 --> 00:47:06.600
So now--

00:47:06.600 --> 00:47:08.970
so basically, I'm just
speculating.

00:47:08.970 --> 00:47:13.030
My own feeling is that there's
certain insurmountable

00:47:13.030 --> 00:47:17.500
metaphysical questions that,
even if we were to get great

00:47:17.500 --> 00:47:19.590
understanding of the brain,
which I have no doubt that

00:47:19.590 --> 00:47:24.240
down the road the techniques
will be such that this will

00:47:24.240 --> 00:47:26.290
look like primitive man.

00:47:26.290 --> 00:47:29.290
But really what it amounts to is
can we bridge that into the

00:47:29.290 --> 00:47:32.480
subjective description.

00:47:32.480 --> 00:47:36.110
In other words, for example,
let's say your foot hurts and

00:47:36.110 --> 00:47:37.890
my foot hurts.

00:47:37.890 --> 00:47:40.620
But we have a whole different
backgrounds,

00:47:40.620 --> 00:47:42.460
for whatever reason.

00:47:42.460 --> 00:47:46.430
We would need to have perfect
information about each of us

00:47:46.430 --> 00:47:50.620
for our entire lives, not
just for this instant.

00:47:50.620 --> 00:47:53.080
And then we would have to
have the same language.

00:47:53.080 --> 00:47:55.820
But even if we had the same
language, like I worked at a

00:47:55.820 --> 00:48:00.010
pain clinic at UCSF, where
people would say their

00:48:00.010 --> 00:48:01.420
paying was a 10.

00:48:01.420 --> 00:48:03.690
But their 10 isn't the
same as your 10.

00:48:03.690 --> 00:48:06.800
So you have the problem of
qualia, or is you're red the

00:48:06.800 --> 00:48:07.710
same as my red.

00:48:07.710 --> 00:48:11.950
Now do I think you
can solve those?

00:48:11.950 --> 00:48:13.420
I like the idea of mystery.

00:48:13.420 --> 00:48:16.060
I know it's not going to be
solved in my lifetime.

00:48:16.060 --> 00:48:17.720
So I enjoy the idea
of mystery.

00:48:17.720 --> 00:48:20.500
But I love the idea
of discovery.

00:48:20.500 --> 00:48:25.160
So it's sort of like
extended foreplay.

00:48:25.160 --> 00:48:26.160
This is not exactly--

00:48:26.160 --> 00:48:30.370
AUDIENCE: So your attitude is
a curiosity and appreciation

00:48:30.370 --> 00:48:30.890
for mystery.

00:48:30.890 --> 00:48:34.600
ROBERT BURTON: Yeah, and If you
get to my age, and you see

00:48:34.600 --> 00:48:37.110
the history of science unfold
in front of your own eyes,

00:48:37.110 --> 00:48:40.530
during your lifetime, we've
made a zillion mistakes.

00:48:40.530 --> 00:48:43.500
Now to think that somewhere down
the road, we won't make

00:48:43.500 --> 00:48:45.510
them is to misunderstand the
nature of human beings.

00:48:48.230 --> 00:48:50.600
Science works in little steps,
little increments forward,

00:48:50.600 --> 00:48:53.600
some steps backward, sideways,
with the idea of moving

00:48:53.600 --> 00:48:57.190
inexorably towards moving
inexorably, but not towards

00:48:57.190 --> 00:48:58.530
any final conclusion.

00:48:58.530 --> 00:49:01.770
Now but that's speculation.

00:49:01.770 --> 00:49:04.280
And that's a novelist looking
at the fact that I like the

00:49:04.280 --> 00:49:07.000
idea there are multiple
explanations.

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.460
AUDIENCE: At the beginning you
showed a picture of the brain

00:49:09.460 --> 00:49:10.840
studying the brain.

00:49:10.840 --> 00:49:14.460
And I think that this is kind of
part of a trend of looking

00:49:14.460 --> 00:49:19.160
more at the history and further
back in the process of

00:49:19.160 --> 00:49:20.430
what we're doing.

00:49:20.430 --> 00:49:25.240
So just acknowledging the fact
that we have these brains that

00:49:25.240 --> 00:49:26.340
have flaws.

00:49:26.340 --> 00:49:29.220
And that's what we're
using to do it.

00:49:29.220 --> 00:49:32.320
And then the next step that
I think about is using

00:49:32.320 --> 00:49:35.440
evolution, so thinking about
the evolved brain

00:49:35.440 --> 00:49:36.780
studying the brain.

00:49:36.780 --> 00:49:38.830
But I'm kind of a skeptic
towards evolutionary

00:49:38.830 --> 00:49:39.700
psychology.

00:49:39.700 --> 00:49:42.170
I guess you might be
somewhat as well.

00:49:42.170 --> 00:49:44.360
Do you have any hope for
bringing evolution to this

00:49:44.360 --> 00:49:45.450
picture more?

00:49:45.450 --> 00:49:49.490
More so than just the very
simple things like, say, the

00:49:49.490 --> 00:49:53.040
size of the visual cortex, but
more complicated things like

00:49:53.040 --> 00:49:55.310
ability to do certain kinds
of computation,

00:49:55.310 --> 00:49:57.820
or things like that.

00:49:57.820 --> 00:49:59.350
ROBERT BURTON: A
couple things.

00:49:59.350 --> 00:50:03.920
First of all, evolution
happened.

00:50:03.920 --> 00:50:06.615
But evolution isn't an entity
with an agenda.

00:50:10.210 --> 00:50:13.280
I don't know how many of you
people know Stephen J Gould

00:50:13.280 --> 00:50:16.130
and the concept of standards,
but it's worth reading about.

00:50:16.130 --> 00:50:25.050
But we assign purpose to
everything but without any

00:50:25.050 --> 00:50:26.070
knowledge that's so.

00:50:26.070 --> 00:50:29.340
So as far as computational
ability, if we're going to

00:50:29.340 --> 00:50:32.370
survive, I think it's more
important we develop empathy

00:50:32.370 --> 00:50:34.730
and compassion and getting
along with others than

00:50:34.730 --> 00:50:35.770
computational ability.

00:50:35.770 --> 00:50:39.800
Because unfortunately, my
concern, which is probably why

00:50:39.800 --> 00:50:42.560
I've written these books, is
that we will get smarter.

00:50:42.560 --> 00:50:46.220
We will get more-- and whatever
tools we can get

00:50:46.220 --> 00:50:47.410
personally--

00:50:47.410 --> 00:50:50.940
let's face it, you guys
are and evolution.

00:50:50.940 --> 00:50:55.850
If you have a PDA or a flash
drive, you can down--

00:50:55.850 --> 00:50:57.850
when I was a neurologist, if
you could just memorize all

00:50:57.850 --> 00:51:00.460
the diseases, and you could walk
around about the latest

00:51:00.460 --> 00:51:01.810
literature, you were a genius.

00:51:01.810 --> 00:51:03.380
Now you don't have to
do any of that.

00:51:03.380 --> 00:51:04.920
So in a way, that
is evolution.

00:51:04.920 --> 00:51:06.660
It's a different kind
of evolution.

00:51:06.660 --> 00:51:09.420
But it isn't making
us any better.

00:51:09.420 --> 00:51:12.300
It isn't solve any problems
in Congress Or

00:51:12.300 --> 00:51:13.640
climate change or anything.

00:51:13.640 --> 00:51:18.340
So if I were to say, I think
that before we worry about

00:51:18.340 --> 00:51:21.400
computational improvements in
the individual, we will have

00:51:21.400 --> 00:51:25.690
them as a group mind,
an extended mind.

00:51:25.690 --> 00:51:27.860
But I don't know that that's
terribly helpful for what

00:51:27.860 --> 00:51:31.210
really counts, which is to
understand that we're fallible

00:51:31.210 --> 00:51:33.790
and that we have to be a bit
humbled that each of our ideas

00:51:33.790 --> 00:51:37.840
comes from an idiosyncratic and
often irrational place,

00:51:37.840 --> 00:51:40.470
even though it may be the best
we can do with science.

00:51:40.470 --> 00:51:42.200
We augment it with science.

00:51:42.200 --> 00:51:44.330
But we still have a lot
of in-built biases.

00:51:44.330 --> 00:51:46.630
Now that's just a personal
sermon, not

00:51:46.630 --> 00:51:48.890
a scientific comment.

