if you guys have time to stick
around, it's a quick--

00:52:21.500 --> 00:52:29.000
I had a patient many years ago,
who had a very, very,

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.160
very, very, very small stroke
was recovered within a few

00:52:31.160 --> 00:52:33.300
hours and was fine but
was an art dealer.

00:52:33.300 --> 00:52:36.670
And he phoned me up
when you go home.

00:52:36.670 --> 00:52:38.460
An he said something
horribles happened.

00:52:38.460 --> 00:52:38.800
I said, what's that?

00:52:38.800 --> 00:52:42.430
He says, my desk has been
replaced by an limitation.

00:52:42.430 --> 00:52:46.560
And what he had was a 12 foot
refractory desk, refectory

00:52:46.560 --> 00:52:48.580
table, that you would you'd have
to take the doors off to

00:52:48.580 --> 00:52:49.490
get it out.

00:52:49.490 --> 00:52:51.500
So it was pretty obvious that
hadn't been replaced.

00:52:51.500 --> 00:52:52.780
And he understood that.

00:52:52.780 --> 00:52:57.150
But when he ran his across the
table top, he said, yes, those

00:52:57.150 --> 00:52:57.800
are the wormholes.

00:52:57.800 --> 00:52:58.470
[INAUDIBLE]

00:52:58.470 --> 00:53:00.680
and those are the scuff
marks and everything.

00:53:00.680 --> 00:53:03.270
They're exactly like before.

00:53:03.270 --> 00:53:05.480
But they don't feel familiar.

00:53:05.480 --> 00:53:09.090
They don't feel like
they used to.

00:53:09.090 --> 00:53:10.400
I said, well, they're
the same size?

00:53:10.400 --> 00:53:13.000
And he was in total agreement
as to the cognitive

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:14.630
aspects of that desk.

00:53:14.630 --> 00:53:16.470
But he could not convince
himself that it wasn't an

00:53:16.470 --> 00:53:18.460
invitation because they
didn't feel familiar.

00:53:18.460 --> 00:53:21.180
And that case was one of the
ones that started me to think

00:53:21.180 --> 00:53:26.090
about the discrepancy between
understanding, cognitive

00:53:26.090 --> 00:53:27.850
understanding--

00:53:27.850 --> 00:53:30.120
he understood that
it was a desk.

00:53:30.120 --> 00:53:34.865
But he couldn't grasp
that it was his.

00:53:34.865 --> 00:53:38.370
And so basically that
sensation is--

00:53:38.370 --> 00:53:39.980
you say with consciousness.

00:53:39.980 --> 00:53:42.830
Consciousness for him was
a combination of the

00:53:42.830 --> 00:53:43.810
intellectual knowledge.

00:53:43.810 --> 00:53:47.120
It came as a fact
and the feeling.

00:53:47.120 --> 00:53:47.690
So yes.

00:53:47.690 --> 00:53:51.200
The Capgras syndrome those
delusions are a form of

00:53:51.200 --> 00:53:54.860
disorders of involuntary
mental states which are

00:53:54.860 --> 00:53:58.480
reflected in consciousness, if
that answers your question.

00:53:58.480 --> 00:53:59.770
AUDIENCE: Well, more
specifically, do you think

00:53:59.770 --> 00:54:03.860
that we can understand
consciousness as sort of a

00:54:03.860 --> 00:54:05.620
continuum that can
be degraded.

00:54:05.620 --> 00:54:07.880
You can measure the level
of degradation

00:54:07.880 --> 00:54:10.350
based on certain defects.

00:54:10.350 --> 00:54:11.570
ROBERT BURTON: Oh, there's
no question.

00:54:11.570 --> 00:54:14.540
If it's like consciousness
goes like that, if

00:54:14.540 --> 00:54:15.030
that's what you mean.

00:54:15.030 --> 00:54:15.340
Yes.

00:54:15.340 --> 00:54:18.646
And you're aware of this,
out the periphery, and

00:54:18.646 --> 00:54:19.980
then it drops off.

00:54:19.980 --> 00:54:23.020
And I suppose all these are
elements-- yes, if you got

00:54:23.020 --> 00:54:24.600
them all together, you'd have
a better idea of what

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:26.010
consciousness is.

00:54:26.010 --> 00:54:29.010
AUDIENCE: So it just reminded
your question on this mind

00:54:29.010 --> 00:54:30.390
versus brain [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:30.390 --> 00:54:32.970
So there in Buddhism
there is this--

00:54:32.970 --> 00:54:35.500
Buddha has this-- there is a
story about Buddha that were

00:54:35.500 --> 00:54:39.440
14 question, if I remember
correctly, that he was never

00:54:39.440 --> 00:54:41.900
ready to make any
answer about.

00:54:41.900 --> 00:54:44.530
So one of them was
something like--

00:54:44.530 --> 00:54:48.260
I think these three questions
were exactly among these 14

00:54:48.260 --> 00:54:50.540
question that Buddha
was never--

00:54:50.540 --> 00:54:53.730
So when he was asked this
question, he was just--

00:54:53.730 --> 00:54:55.150
didn't say anything.

00:54:55.150 --> 00:55:00.380
So I just wondered whether your
attitude is more like--

00:55:00.380 --> 00:55:03.630
is something that is not
meaningful question?

00:55:03.630 --> 00:55:06.100
Of is it something that--

00:55:06.100 --> 00:55:08.900
so that it's inherently a
stupid question or is it

00:55:08.900 --> 00:55:12.340
something that maybe answered
in the future?

00:55:12.340 --> 00:55:14.410
ROBERT BURTON: There are
different kinds of questions.

00:55:14.410 --> 00:55:17.370
There are some that are
meaningful but seem like

00:55:17.370 --> 00:55:18.450
they're very difficult.

00:55:18.450 --> 00:55:21.920
Obviously, it's meaningful ask
what is consciousness.

00:55:21.920 --> 00:55:25.840
On the other hand, to ask what
is free will is a different

00:55:25.840 --> 00:55:26.450
kind of question.

00:55:26.450 --> 00:55:28.900
Because, to me, free will,
the very question--

00:55:28.900 --> 00:55:30.340
first of all, the word free
will doesn't make sense.

00:55:30.340 --> 00:55:32.500
Because what kind of will
would there be?

00:55:32.500 --> 00:55:35.270
And you think, well, how is it
that everybody writes books on

00:55:35.270 --> 00:55:38.070
free will without even saying
what does that word mean?

00:55:38.070 --> 00:55:41.440
Now if you go back and think
about it from a historical

00:55:41.440 --> 00:55:44.960
perspective, it was really
pounded into the public mind

00:55:44.960 --> 00:55:47.250
by Augustine in the year 300.

00:55:47.250 --> 00:55:51.300
Now why is it that 1800 years
later, we're still debating

00:55:51.300 --> 00:55:53.120
it, when after 1800 years, you
haven't got an answers?

00:55:53.120 --> 00:55:54.840
So to me, one possibility
is maybe the

00:55:54.840 --> 00:55:56.590
question makes no sense.

00:55:56.590 --> 00:55:59.730
But then it gets down to how you
think about determinism,

00:55:59.730 --> 00:56:01.990
and various levels of
determinism versus emergent

00:56:01.990 --> 00:56:04.770
behavior, and then you guys
standing here talk about

00:56:04.770 --> 00:56:06.820
compatiblism which
makes no sense.

00:56:06.820 --> 00:56:10.560
But what it amounts to is the
original question doesn't--

00:56:10.560 --> 00:56:14.160
for example, what came
before the beginning?

00:56:14.160 --> 00:56:16.600
Well, that's a language
question.

00:56:16.600 --> 00:56:18.280
It's like it Wittgenstein
once said, it is

00:56:18.280 --> 00:56:19.660
afternoon on the sun.

00:56:19.660 --> 00:56:21.580
Now I you have to laugh
when you hear that.

00:56:21.580 --> 00:56:24.460
You go, that's a
great sentence.

00:56:24.460 --> 00:56:26.950
We should learn from those
kind of nonsense things.

00:56:26.950 --> 00:56:30.290
And this book, How Something
Comes from Nothing--

00:56:30.290 --> 00:56:32.600
all the latest physics--

00:56:32.600 --> 00:56:38.320
well, that again is an attempt
to distort a paradox.

00:56:38.320 --> 00:56:41.330
So those questions that are
really meaningful, the really

00:56:41.330 --> 00:56:43.300
hard to grasp, like
how does the brain

00:56:43.300 --> 00:56:45.920
create subjective response.

00:56:45.920 --> 00:56:47.580
And there are just like, huh?

00:56:47.580 --> 00:56:49.420
Why bother to ask
that question?

00:56:49.420 --> 00:56:51.240
So it runs the gamut.

00:56:51.240 --> 00:56:52.220
But that's my cynicism.

00:56:52.220 --> 00:56:53.080
That's not skepticism.

00:56:53.080 --> 00:56:55.250
That's cynicism.

00:56:55.250 --> 00:56:56.500
They're closely allied.

